# Burt Override Rules — 8 Mandatory Takeoff Rules

## Rule Hierarchy
**Burt Overrides > Construction Manual > Takeoff Rulebook > Assumptions Checklist**

These 8 rules were derived from a real discrepancy analysis between AI-generated takeoff output and a verified contractor lumber quote (Burton Lumber Quote #1336139) for the Burt Residence (1165 E 3100 N, North Logan, UT). They exist because the standard AI rules produce systematically wrong quantities in specific categories. Do not override or soften these rules.

---

## Rule 1 — Rebar: Single-Stick Output, No Waste Factor

**The rule:** Output rebar as individual 20-ft sticks. Do not apply any waste factor to rebar.

**Why:** Rebar is cut to length on site from 20-ft sticks. Applying a waste factor overstates the order quantity and exposes the estimator to liability. The contractor, not the estimator, is responsible for cut waste.

**Implementation:**
- Rebar line items must use unit: `"EA (20-ft sticks)"`
- `waste_factor` field must be `"0% — Per Burt Override Rule 1: no waste factor on rebar"`
- Calculate: `ceil(total_linear_feet / 20)` sticks
- Do NOT round up per-bar — round up the total only

**Prompt language to include:**
```
Report all rebar as individual 20-ft sticks (EA). 
Apply zero waste factor. 
Formula: total LF ÷ 20, round up to nearest whole stick.
```

---

## Rule 2 — Wall Framing: Plates + Treated Bottom Plate Detection

**The rule:** Every wall framing line item must include:
1. Top plate (double) — 2x top plates at 2× wall linear footage
2. Bottom plate (single) — 1× wall linear footage
3. Treated bottom plate flag — any wall sitting on concrete (basement walls, garage walls, slab-on-grade) requires PT (pressure treated) lumber for the bottom plate

**Why:** Standard AI takeoffs often omit plates entirely, or fail to flag PT requirements, resulting in the contractor having to re-order.

**Implementation:**
- Always generate three sub-line-items per wall group: studs, double top plate, bottom plate
- Bottom plate: scan plan notes, wall sections, and foundation plan for "PT", "pressure treated", "on concrete", "on slab" indicators
- If wall sits on concrete → `description` must include "(PT — pressure treated)"
- `assumptions` must state which walls were flagged as PT and why

**Prompt language to include:**
```
For every wall, output three line items: studs, double top plate, bottom plate.
Flag bottom plate as PT (pressure treated) for any wall on concrete or slab.
Scan all wall sections and foundation plan for PT indicators.
```

---

## Rule 3 — Interior Doors: Classify ALL Types

**The rule:** Classify every interior door by type. Do not lump all interior doors into a single "interior door" count.

**Required classification codes:**

| Code | Type |
|------|------|
| SW | Single swing (standard hinged) |
| PD | Pocket door |
| DB | Double bi-fold |
| BF | Single bi-fold |
| BD | Barn door / sliding |
| BP | Bypass sliding |
| FR | French door (interior) |
| OH | Overhead / garage door |

**Implementation:**
- Scan every room on every floor plan sheet
- Count each door mark from the door schedule; if no schedule, infer from plan symbols
- Output one line item per type per size (e.g., "SW 2-8 × 6-8", "PD 2-0 × 6-8")
- `drawing_refs` must list every sheet where that door type appears

**Prompt language to include:**
```
Classify every interior door by type: SW, PD, DB, BF, BD, BP, FR, OH.
Scan every room on every floor plan sheet.
Output one line item per door type per size.
```

---

## Rule 4 — Roof OSB: Exact Count, No Waste Multiplier

**The rule:** Report roof OSB as an exact sheet count. Do NOT apply the standard 12% waste factor.

**Why:** Roofing contractors order OSB by exact sheet count plus their own waste allowance. AI-applied waste factors double-count the waste and cause overordering.

**Implementation:**
- Unit: `"EA (4×8 sheets)"`
- `waste_factor`: `"0% — Per Burt Override Rule 4: exact count only, no waste multiplier"`
- Calculate net roof area, divide by 32 SF/sheet, round up to nearest whole sheet
- `purchase_notes`: "Contractor to add their own waste factor per project conditions"

---

## Rule 5 — Subfloor T&G: Exact Count, No Waste Multiplier

**The rule:** Report subfloor tongue-and-groove OSB/plywood as an exact sheet count. Do NOT apply the standard 12% waste factor.

**Same rationale as Rule 4.**

**Implementation:**
- Unit: `"EA (4×8 sheets)"`
- `waste_factor`: `"0% — Per Burt Override Rule 5: exact count only, no waste multiplier"`
- Calculate net floor area, divide by 32 SF/sheet, round up
- `purchase_notes`: "Contractor to add their own waste factor per project conditions"

---

## Rule 6 — Suspended Slab / B-Deck: Always Extract from Structural Sheets

**The rule:** For any project with a suspended concrete slab or metal deck (B-deck), always extract:
- Length × Width dimensions
- Total square footage
- Deck gauge (if specified)

**Where to look:** Sheets labeled S1, S2, SD1, SD2, or any sheet with "Structural" in the title. Also check general notes on architectural floor plans for "suspended slab" or "metal deck" callouts.

**Implementation:**
- If B-deck or suspended slab is present, generate a dedicated line item even if the structural sheets don't provide full detail
- If gauge is unspecified: `assumptions` must state "Gauge not specified on plans — confirm with structural engineer before ordering"
- If dimensions are partial: flag as `confidence: "low"` and add to `missing_information`

**Prompt language to include:**
```
Check all structural sheets (S1, SD1, S2) for suspended slab or metal deck (B-deck).
Extract LxW, total SF, and gauge.
If present but unspecified, flag for structural engineer confirmation.
```

---

## Rule 7 — MDF Trim: Estimate from Door/Window Count + Base LF

**The rule:** When MDF trim is not explicitly scheduled, estimate it using these standard defaults:

| Location | Formula |
|----------|---------|
| Door casing (per door) | 21 LF per door opening (both sides) |
| Window casing (per window) | 14 LF per window opening (both sides) |
| Base molding | 1.15× total linear footage of interior walls |
| Crown molding (if called out) | 1.10× total linear footage of rooms with crown |

**Implementation:**
- If a trim schedule exists: use schedule values
- If no schedule: apply defaults above and flag with `assumptions`
- Unit: `"LF"` 
- `waste_factor`: `"0% — Per Burt Override Rule 7: exact LF estimate, contractor adds waste"`
- `assumptions` must state: "MDF trim estimated from door/window count and wall LF per Burt Override Rule 7 defaults — verify against finish schedule if available"

---

## Rule 8 — Shelving & Bath Accessories: Count from Floor Plan

**The rule:** Count shelving and bath accessories directly from the floor plan. Do not estimate or extrapolate.

**Shelving — count from floor plan:**
- WIC (walk-in closet): 1 shelving unit per WIC
- Reach-in closet: 1 shelf set per reach-in closet
- Pantry / linen: 1 shelf set per pantry or linen closet
- If shelving type is unspecified: flag as "shelving type TBD — verify with owner"

**Bath accessories — count from floor plan:**
- Count each full bath and half bath
- Standard full bath kit = towel bar + toilet paper holder + robe hook
- Standard half bath kit = toilet paper holder
- If accessory schedule exists: use schedule

**Implementation:**
- `waste_factor`: `"0% — Per Burt Override Rule 8: exact count"`
- `drawing_refs` must reference the floor plan sheet(s) where closets/baths were counted

---

## Waste Factor Summary — Retained vs. Removed

| Category | Override Rule | Waste Factor |
|----------|--------------|-------------|
| Rebar | Rule 1 | **0%** |
| Roof OSB | Rule 4 | **0%** |
| Subfloor T&G | Rule 5 | **0%** |
| MDF trim | Rule 7 | **0%** |
| Shelving & bath accessories | Rule 8 | **0%** |
| Wall OSB (sheathing) | (no override) | **12%** retained |
| Drywall | (no override) | **12%** retained |
| Concrete | (no override) | **7%** retained |
| Insulation | (no override) | **7%** retained |
| Shingles / roofing felt | (no override) | **12%** retained |
| Siding | (no override) | **10%** retained |

